snippet.textDisplay:
How Palpatine was done in this movie does not do him justice. He was the star of the scene in literally every SW movie that had him, but in this movie he's brought in with no build up or explanation, looks terrible (in a bad makeup kind of way, not in a "oh he's old and messed up" kind of way), has cringey dialogue ("I am all the Sith") and terribly shoe-horned in prequel quotes ("goooood", "dew it", "the dark side of the force is a pathway to many abilities some would consider to be unnatural"), his OP lightning not being built up enough so it just seems like a BS OP ability, as well as the energy absorption. I'm okay with OP abilities, but they need to be explained first and need to demonstrate some sort of drawback to it's power or some kind of struggle to get it, otherwise it just seems like anyone can pull OP abilities out of their ass. There were a lot of things that I liked about this movie, but instead of the previous movies where Palps improved the movies by being in them, in this movie he's so badly done that he actually makes the movie significantly worse than if he wasn't in the movie at all.

In fact, if Kylo Ren was the main antagonist of this movie, it would be so much better. Maybe if the wayfinders were used to find a sort of Sith library or something to make Kylo more powerful, the adventure could be to have Kylo and Rey (and friends) race after this library to replace the trying to find Palps' planet adventure. Everything else about the movie could be the same, Kylo becoming Ben and fighting the Knights of Ren (and hopefully having some dialogue between them), and Lando and everyone else having the same final space battle except against just the First Order's ships, tying all loose ends. This would also be a happier ending with Ben as well as Rey still being alive, and I'd put in a final scene showing the reconstruction, like establishing a new Republic that addresses the flaws of the old systems of government.

I disagree that Rise of Skywalker retcons The Last Jedi and that you can watch the sequel trilogy by leaving it out. It actually takes the best elements from episode 8 and evolves them into the story:
1) Kylo Ren’s conflict and inner torment continues to haunt him despite his ascendancy within the First Order to Supreme Leader.
2) Kylo and Rey’s Force bond is now central to the story and plays a part in getting them to confront Palpatine and overcome the Knights of Ren.
3) Leia’s Force powers in TLJ make more sense as Rise reveals that she underwent training with Luke.
4) The Resistance’s rebuilding is in full swing following their decimation (the Battle of Crait is mentioned in Rise).
5) There’s concern that the galaxy will not heed Lando’s call to arms due to their fear (Leia’s unanswered distress call is mentioned in Rise).
6) Luke mentors Rey that “confronting your fear is the destiny of the Jedi”, just as Luke confronted his own failure by confronting Kylo. “Failure, the greatest teacher is” as Yoda provides Luke with his final lesson.
7) After leading so many Resistance fighters to their deaths in the Siege of D’Qar, Poe fears that history will repeat itself before Lando reappears.
8) In episode 8, Rian realised Rey’s worst fears in that she was initially not from any heritage of note. JJ evolves that notion to provide her with the second worst possible answer: born from evil.

In a recent interview, Chris Terrio and JJ Abrams were quoted as not feeling hindered by how The Last Jedi ended but felt like it opened new doors so they could take these elements and form the core of the final chapter. Ultimately, they brought to a close a disjointed trilogy as best they could while honoring everything that came before it, and that deserves high praise imho.

Always interesting to hear your viewpoint! I saw a couple things differently and wondered if anyone else saw something similar.

1. I interpreted Palpatine's sucking the life energy from Rey and Ben to be related to the power to escape death that Anakin was hoping to discover to save Padme. In his short preamble to that, he mentions how the Force dyad is incredibly rare, and though I forget the exact phrasing now, I thought he also said it made certain abilities possible that aren't normally possible (to me, that echoed back to how, paraphrasing, "only one has ever harnessed this power"). It would be a sort of poetic way to bring that story line full circle, or at least lend some explanation to what that ability entails and why more people haven't used it.

2. I didn't especially like her using the Skywalker name at the end either. But I thought that was more about how Luke and Leia became like her adoptive parents, more so than that they trained her. This angle definitely gives it a different feel and meaning, less about Jedi lineages than it is about an orphan who found a home.

snippet.textDisplay: I'm a huge huge Star Wars fan I've always been and will be a fan. I've seen all 3 of the sequel films in the cinema. But I came out devastated or hugely disappointed every time. All 3 movies had incredible music by John Williams who is a GOD! I love his work! That's about all the good things they have in common. This film was the most beautiful out of all 9 films I loved General Pryde finally a capable leader who will give you chills as Tarkin did. But overall I didn't like the cinematography or the VFX work. I don't think I've ever felt like I've had a problem with cinematography in a quote and quote professional Hollywood film. I was just sad and frustrated. I've felt that J.J. Abrams was an incompetent writer/director.  Which made me even more depressed, because I know he is a huge fan who has poured his heart and soul into this film. Before and during film school I watched J. J.'s lecture that he delivered in a TED talk years before Disney bought Lucasarts. In this lecture, he spoke about his love of Star Wars among other things. Anyways going back to the film. The film was a narrative disaster. It was lacking any creativity and craftsmanship. He took the rules of writing and threw it all out of the window. Within the first 2-3 minutes, my friend wanted to bet me that Kylo and Rey will end up tag-teaming against Palpatine. To which I responded with a no, because I didn't want to bet on a sure thing. We both knew ahead of time how it will and the same goes for the kissing. I think almost any film which has an ending this predictable has a failed script at least in some respects. Giving away Palpatine in the first minute is a huge-huge problem, both in the film and its marketing material. The film lacks almost any sort of real obstacle's to get to Palpatine I didn't doubt for a second that both of them would get to him. The film is full of meaningless sidequests without any real obstacles. Like how C3PO-s memory wipe had no real sense of obstacle it was just way to drag the story onwards without real dramatic progression. They never have to think hard, fight hard, suffer to get anything, all they need to do is travel to places and everything will fall into their laps. The way death is handled here (too) just makes it really hard to take any death scenes seriously. But anyway the 1 scene that showed me total incompetence as a writer and director is when they flew to that gorgeous ice place (planet?).  They go into a small hole and dock the ship so that R2-D2 can download an intel. They have downloaded the Intel and that's when the imperial's start to appear in the whole. This does not create suspense!!! If they wanted to create real suspense all they had to do without draging the scene out. Is to change the order of the clips in the editing timeline. If they're still nowhere near close to downloading the intel (which didn't seem to crucial it should've felt more crucial) when TIE fighters are already close by then there would've been a real sense of suspense. And have them escape in the last minute. And then J.J. also broke (after breaking a bunch of writing rules) all the in-universe rules that were set up by the previous films.  I hope he will make something great again like Super8, but this was disheartening. I love the channel keep it up, it's so much fun even if we don't agree on this film! Thanks for all your hard work!

snippet.textDisplay:
I just finished watching it.

Yikes.

This entire movie was one big deus ex machina, full of events that just so happened perfectly to drive the story forward. The only, sole purpose for its inception was to repair any mistakes that started in the force awakens and the last jedi. In this regard, it did well.

As a movie, it was trash. Imo. It moved wayyyy too fast, and never gve you time to stop and process what just went on. It is a never ending sequence of events with no pauses in the action to breathe a little.

Rey is still overpowered as fuck. Literally mind tricking a PAIR of troopers (Usually takes one YEARS to master it on one person), she literally just grabs a flying ship out of thin air while it's moving... Master Yoda only barely brought Red 5 up out of the swamp in Empire... Just so happens to be a Palpatine which woopdie doo, solves that little problem of why she is so crazy powerful in the first place. It's an easy out for a mistake made a few years ago in TFA.

Oh.. And don't forget the perfect timing and decision making events summed up as "A feeling". And the power of friendship being driven home like a nail in your own coffin.

This sequel trilogy was a mistake from the beginning. I knew it would be from the moment it was announced.

I am very butthurt. Rightfully so.
